summary:
Reaffirms concern over negative effect of violence in Darfur on regional stability,

Commends UNAMID's efforts and reiterates full support,

Welcoming reports of Secretary-General,

Noting completion of review on under-reporting allegations,

Determining situation in Sudan constitutes threat to international peace and security,

1. Decides to extend UNAMID's mandate until 30 June 2016 with 15,845 military personnel, 1,583 police personnel and 13 formed police units,

2. Reiterates endorsement of UNAMID's revised strategic priorities: protection of civilians, facilitation of humanitarian assistance, mediation between Government and non-signatory armed movements, and support to community conflict mediation,

3. Notes certain elements of UNAMID's mandate are no longer relevant or will transition to other entities,

4. Underlines UNAMID must prioritize: protection of civilians, particularly women and children.
The Security Council,

1. Decides to extend the mandate of UNAMID and requests it to focus on: 
(a) enhancing early warning; proactive military deployment and patrolling in high-risk areas; 
more effective responses to threats of violence against civilians; securing IDP camps and areas of return; 
and ensuring safe and unhindered humanitarian access;

2. Emphasizes UNAMID's Chapter VII mandate to protect civilians and ensure its own personnel's security; 

3. Urges UNAMID to deter threats against itself and its mandate;

4. Stresses that any refinement of the mission should be based on progress against benchmarks and conditions on the ground;

5. Commends the Joint Special Representative's efforts to revitalize the peace process and increase its inclusiveness;

6. Welcomes progress in implementing some elements of the DDPD but deplores continuing delays; 

7. Demands that all parties cease all acts of violence and commit to a sustained and permanent ceasefire;

8. Reaffirms support for a Darfur-based internal dialogue and welcomes the completion of the first phase of the DIDC;

9. Calls for an urgent end to inter-tribal clashes and criminality;

10. Expresses concern over the proliferation of arms and requests UNAMID to cooperate with the Panel of Experts;

11. Commends troop- and police-contributing countries and calls for continued efforts to address equipment and self-sustainment shortfalls;

12. Strongly condemns attacks on UNAMID and demands that those responsible be held accountable;
